This paper discusses a method for using statistical language modeling to audit the structural regularity of electronic dictionaries. The paper focuses on the use of XML-based standards to represent lexical entries, which suggests a focus on natural language processing (NLP) and computational linguistics (cs.CL). Additionally, the use of statistical language modeling to detect irregularities suggests a focus on information retrieval (cs.IR), machine learning (cs.LG), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the use of XML trees to represent dictionary entries suggests a focus on data structures (cs.DS). Therefore, the most likely arXiv CS sub-category for this paper is cs.CL, followed by cs.IR, cs.LG, cs.AI, and cs.DS.
